#### Issue description

The code does not compile when declaring std::chrono::duration<float> with a float representation. Not sure if this issue happens on Linux.

/Library/Developer/CommandLineTools/usr/bin/../include/c++/v1/chrono:742:53: error: invalid operands to binary
      expression ('_Cr' (aka 'float') and '_Cr')
    return _Cd(static_cast<_Cr>(_Cd(__lhs).count()) % static_cast<_Cr>(_Cd(__rhs).count()));
               ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~ ^ ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
/Users/xxxxx/pybind11/include/pybind11/chrono.h:90:54: note: in instantiation of function template
      specialization 'std::__1::chrono::operator%<float, std::__1::ratio<1, 1>, long long, std::__1::ratio<1, 1>
      >' requested here
                               duration_cast<us_t>(d % seconds(1)).count());
                                                     ^
.....
..... <more snipped out>


#### Reproducible example code
```
#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
#include <pybind11/chrono.h>
namespace py = pybind11;
class FloatDurationTest {
public:
    std::chrono::duration<float> fduration;
};

PYBIND11_PLUGIN(float_duration_test) {
    py::module m("float_duration_test", "float duration test plugin");
    pybind11::class_<FloatDurationTest>(m, "FloatDurationTest")
            // constructors
            .def(pybind11::init<>())
            .def_readwrite("fduration", &FloatDurationTest::fduration)
            ;
    return m.ptr();
}
```

In PYBIND11_MODULE, if the name is also a namespace, compilation fails.  FWIW this was not a problem with the old-school PYBIND11_PLUGIN

E.g.:
```
#include <ChebMix/ChebMix.h>// (defining the ChebMix namespace)
...
PYBIND11_MODULE(ChebMix, m) {
    m.doc() = "ChebMix module";
    init_ChebTools(m);
    init_ChebMix(m);
}
```
yields
```
D:\Code\ChebMix\src\pybind11_wrapper.cpp(156): error C2882: 'ChebMix': illegal use of namespace identifier in expression
```

Is there a solution or workaround?
